43:39.974 --> 43:41.974
Well, if it's cold, choke it.

43:42.099 --> 43:43.641
And pump it.

43:43.766 --> 43:45.141
How many time?

43:49.099 --> 43:50.932
Ed Crane?

43:54.557 --> 43:56.473
I'm Crane.

43:56.556 --> 43:59.098
- Come on outside.
- Sure.

44:14.973 --> 44:17.806
I'm officer Persky.
This is Krebs.

44:19.723 --> 44:21.515
Well, we goin'?

44:26.765 --> 44:27.805
Cigarette?

44:31.554 --> 44:32.679
Right.

44:34.679 --> 44:37.013
Pete's got some news for ya.

44:42.846 --> 44:44.221
Look, pal, um,

44:46.138 --> 44:48.013
It's a tough break, but, um,

44:49.804 --> 44:51.596
Well, damn it,
your wife's been pinched.

44:51.721 --> 44:54.679
They sent us around
to tell you.

44:56.554 --> 44:59.179
They sent us around to tell you.
We pulled the detail.

45:01.095 --> 45:03.428
My wife?

45:03.553 --> 45:06.845
Yeah, they brung her down
to county jail.

45:07.928 --> 45:09.137
Homicide.

45:09.220 --> 45:11.053
Well, embezzlement...

45:11.178 --> 45:12.762
And homicide.

45:12.887 --> 45:16.428
Guy named David Brewster.
He's the guy she...

45:16.553 --> 45:18.053
H- He's the decedent.

45:18.803 --> 45:20.470
I don't understand.

45:20.553 --> 45:22.052
He's the dead guy.

45:22.177 --> 45:25.927
Yeah, it's a tough break.

45:27.552 --> 45:29.719
Visiting ends at 5:00.

45:29.844 --> 45:32.011
Oh, uh, missed it today,
but, uh,

45:33.010 --> 45:34.801
You can go see her tomorrow.

45:36.551 --> 45:38.176
Sorry, pal.

45:38.218 --> 45:40.551
They sent us to tell ya.

45:42.385 --> 45:44.176
Crab detail.

46:07.800 --> 46:10.592
- Hello, Walter.
- Hello, Ed.

46:13.549 --> 46:16.549
Thanks.
Thanks for seein' me at home.

46:16.674 --> 46:19.466
Oh, hell.
Want a drink?

46:21.466 --> 46:22.466
Uh, no, thanks.

46:22.549 --> 46:24.799
You sure you don't need one?

46:24.883 --> 46:26.758
I'm fine.

46:27.924 --> 46:30.008
- Boy.
- Yeah.

46:31.508 --> 46:32.966
Jesus.

46:35.883 --> 46:37.840
So, uh,
What do I, uh...

46:37.923 --> 46:40.423
Of course, uh, I, uh...

46:41.173 --> 46:43.673
It's out of my league.

46:43.798 --> 46:48.132
No, I... no, I-I do probate
and real estate...

46:48.215 --> 46:49.507
And title search.

46:50.965 --> 46:54.673
I'd be absolutely worthless,
somethin' like this. Absolutely worthless.

46:57.048 --> 46:58.423
Excuse me.

46:59.965 --> 47:01.965
I just finished dinner.

47:05.714 --> 47:09.214
Frankly, Doris'd be better off
with the county defender.

47:09.506 --> 47:12.421
- He a good man?
- Bert's okay.

47:12.546 --> 47:15.171
Yeah, he...
he's a good man.

47:16.796 --> 47:19.796
Listen. I won't kid you, Ed.

47:19.880 --> 47:23.671
Uh, there's nobody around here
has any experience with this kind of thing.

47:24.880 --> 47:27.171
I hear they're bringing a prosecutor up.

47:27.213 --> 47:29.213
From, uh, Sacramento.

47:31.046 --> 47:34.713
It's a capital offense.
They're taking it seriously.

47:34.838 --> 47:36.796
- So...
- They're taking it seriously.

47:36.880 --> 47:39.213
So, what-what, uh...

47:39.505 --> 47:41.963
Do you want any more coffee, dad?
Oh, hi, Mr. Crane.

47:43.045 --> 47:44.587
Hello, Rachel.

47:46.920 --> 47:48.837
I was so sorry to hear.

47:50.545 --> 47:51.837
Yeah, thanks.

47:51.962 --> 47:54.170
- Coffee, Ed?
- No, thanks.

47:54.212 --> 47:56.961
- Ah, no, thanks, honey. We're...
- Okay, dad.

47:57.044 --> 47:59.128
It was good to see you again,
Mr. Crane.

48:03.253 --> 48:04.669
Damn.

48:05.919 --> 48:07.169
A good kid.

48:07.211 --> 48:08.669
Jesus...

48:13.919 --> 48:17.668
Who do you think?

48:17.710 --> 48:20.168
Lloyd Garroway in San Francisco.

48:20.877 --> 48:22.460
Probity.

48:22.543 --> 48:27.210
You know, nobody ever said anything iffy
about Lloyd Garroway.

48:28.210 --> 48:30.168
He's conservative.

48:30.460 --> 48:33.418
Jury might like that.
Might like that here.

48:35.710 --> 48:36.793
Probity.

48:36.877 --> 48:40.710
So, he's, uh,
the best man for...

48:40.835 --> 48:42.085
No.

48:42.210 --> 48:45.960
The best, the money-is-no-object best,

48:46.043 --> 48:49.625
any lawyer'll tell you,
is Freddy Riedenschneider from...

48:52.166 --> 48:53.791
Sacramento.

48:55.125 --> 48:57.833
I don't know
how you're fixed for money.

48:57.958 --> 48:59.833
- But he's...
- The best.

48:59.958 --> 49:01.416
The best, yeah.

49:04.041 --> 49:06.000
Riedenschneider.

49:15.041 --> 49:16.875
No question about it.

49:46.539 --> 49:47.664
Honey.

50:04.705 --> 50:06.580
I brought your makeup.

50:08.497 --> 50:09.663
Glasses.

50:16.830 --> 50:18.705
What happened to you?

50:18.830 --> 50:21.122
I don't know
what's goin' on... I...

50:24.705 --> 50:26.579
I don't know
what happened to Big Dave.

50:26.704 --> 50:28.496
I know some of it.

50:28.579 --> 50:31.828
Irregullarities in the books, they said.
Can I explain it?

50:32.995 --> 50:35.120
You don't have to
explain anything.

50:35.203 --> 50:38.120
I did help him cook the books, Ed.
I did do that.

50:44.953 --> 50:46.120
Should I...

50:47.911 --> 50:51.578
Should I tell you
why I changed the books?

50:54.870 --> 50:57.536
You don't have to
tell me anything.

50:58.952 --> 51:00.785
No, no, no!

51:02.119 --> 51:03.494
Jesus Christ!

51:18.452 --> 51:20.160
My books used to be perfect.

51:20.244 --> 51:23.784
Anyone could open 'em up
and make sense of the whole goddamn store.

51:28.451 --> 51:30.409
I knew we'd pay for it.

51:30.534 --> 51:32.075
I don't care what it costs!

51:32.200 --> 51:35.533
This is when you come together.

51:35.658 --> 51:37.158
Well, that's awfully
generous of you, Frank.

51:37.450 --> 51:40.450
The hell with it.
The hell with it, Eddie.

51:40.575 --> 51:42.492
This is when you come together.

51:42.575 --> 51:44.492
This is family.

51:47.950 --> 51:51.158
They're just people
like you and me, Ed.

51:51.450 --> 51:52.950
Remember that.

51:54.533 --> 51:56.492
Just people.

51:56.575 --> 52:00.950
They gotta put up the big front
so that people will trust 'em with their money.

52:01.033 --> 52:03.491
This is why the big lobby, Ed.

52:03.574 --> 52:08.407
But they put their pants on
one leg at a time just like you and me.

52:10.157 --> 52:13.741
They, too, use the toilet, Ed,
in spite of appearances.

52:13.866 --> 52:16.906
And their money will be secured
by the barber shop.

52:17.031 --> 52:19.990
A rock.
A rock, the barber shop.

52:20.115 --> 52:21.906
Mr. Raffo.

52:22.031 --> 52:23.698
Yes, sir?

52:23.823 --> 52:25.781
Could you come with me,
please?

52:25.906 --> 52:28.031
Sure.
Can Ed come too?

52:28.156 --> 52:29.615
Mister...

52:30.198 --> 52:33.115
Crane.
Ed Crane.

52:33.198 --> 52:36.072
You also have an interest
in the securing porperty?

52:37.530 --> 52:39.155
He's a barber.

52:39.239 --> 52:42.780
- Second chair.
- Not an owner.

52:42.905 --> 52:46.822
No, he's, uh, family.
He's my brother-in-law.

52:46.947 --> 52:50.155
It would be best
if he waited here.

53:28.070 --> 53:29.903
The barber shop.

53:33.903 --> 53:37.903
Doris and Frank's father had worked
30 years to own it free and clear.

53:38.028 --> 53:42.027
Now it got signed over to the bank,
and the bank signed some over to Frank.

53:42.152 --> 53:45.569
And Frank signed the money
to Freddy Riedenschneider.

53:45.694 --> 53:47.819
Who got into town
two days later...

53:47.902 --> 53:50.777
And told me to meet him
at Da Vinci's for lunch.

53:53.486 --> 53:55.986
Not fried, poached.
Three of 'em for two minutes.

53:56.111 --> 53:59.110
Strip steak, medium rare,
flapjacks, potatoes, tomato juice...

53:59.193 --> 54:00.526
And plenty of hot coffee.

54:01.568 --> 54:04.151
- You have any Prairie Oysters?
- No, sir.

54:04.235 --> 54:07.401
Then bring me a fruit cocktail
while I wait.

54:09.818 --> 54:11.818
- You're Crane?
- Yeah.

54:11.943 --> 54:13.484
Barber, right?

54:13.609 --> 54:15.484
I'm Freddy Riedenschneider.
Hungry?

54:15.567 --> 54:16.817
Uh, not really.

54:16.900 --> 54:19.734
They tell me the chow's okay here.
I made some inquiries.

54:21.192 --> 54:24.275
Look, I don't want to waste your time,
so I'll eat while we talk.

54:24.442 --> 54:25.567
Do you mind?
You don't mind.

54:25.692 --> 54:28.525
While I'm in town
I'm staying at the Hotel Metropole.

54:28.609 --> 54:32.609
Turandot Suite. Yeah, it's goofy.
They named their suites after operas.

54:32.692 --> 54:34.650
Room's okay, though.
I poked around.

54:34.734 --> 54:37.109
I'm having 'em hold it for me.
I'll be back and forth.

54:37.192 --> 54:40.650
So, in addition to my retainer,
you're paying hotel,

54:40.734 --> 54:42.484
Living expenses, secretarial,

54:42.567 --> 54:45.817
Private eye, if we need to make inquiries,
head shrinker, should we go that way.

54:45.899 --> 54:48.024
We'll talk about appeals
if, as and when.

54:48.149 --> 54:51.815
- For now, has she confessed?
- No, of course not. She didn't do it.

54:51.898 --> 54:55.440
Good. That helps. Not that she didn't do it
That she didn't confess.

54:55.523 --> 54:59.440
Course, There's ways to deal with a confession,
but that's one less thing to think about.

54:59.523 --> 55:02.607
Now, interview. I'm seeing her tomorrow.
You sholud be there 3:00.

55:02.690 --> 55:04.940
One more thing.
You keep your mouth shut.

55:05.023 --> 55:07.815
I get the lay of the land,
I tell you what to say.

55:07.898 --> 55:11.148
No talking out of school.
What's out of school?
Everything's out of school.

55:11.232 --> 55:13.773
I do the talking.
You keep your trap shut.

55:13.898 --> 55:15.940
I'm an attorney. You're a barber.
You don't know anything.

55:19.064 --> 55:19.981
Okay.

55:20.064 --> 55:22.522
Good. Any questions,
give me a ring.

55:22.647 --> 55:24.981
Turandot suite.
If I'm out, leave a message.

55:26.189 --> 55:29.106
Sure you don't want anything?
No? Okay.

55:29.189 --> 55:31.147
You're okay, pal.

55:31.439 --> 55:33.772
You're okay, she's okay,
everything's gonna be hunky...

55:33.856 --> 55:35.897
And the...
and the flapjacks, honey.

55:43.105 --> 55:44.521
There they were,

55:47.521 --> 55:49.730
All going about their business.

55:51.895 --> 55:53.854
It seem like I knew a secret,

55:53.937 --> 55:57.437
A bigger one, even,
than what had really happened to Big Dave,

55:57.520 --> 56:00.395
Something none of them knew.

56:00.520 --> 56:02.979
Like I had made it to the outside somehow,

56:03.104 --> 56:05.729
And they were all still struggling
way down below.

56:29.186 --> 56:30.394
Ann.

56:31.686 --> 56:33.019
Hello, Ed.

56:33.893 --> 56:36.143
Would you like to come in, Ann?

56:37.685 --> 56:40.143
No. No, it's very late.

56:44.227 --> 56:46.810
I'm so sorry about your loss.

56:52.185 --> 56:56.392
Course you know that Doris
had nothing to do with it.

56:56.517 --> 56:58.601
Nothing at all.

56:59.101 --> 57:00.976
I know.

57:01.809 --> 57:04.017
Don't worry, Ed.

57:04.934 --> 57:06.892
I came to tell you...

57:07.017 --> 57:10.392
And you should tell Doris...

57:10.476 --> 57:11.476
Yeah?

57:22.517 --> 57:26.391
You know how Big Dave loved camping
and the out of doors?

57:28.765 --> 57:29.849
Yeah.

57:29.974 --> 57:34.057
We went camping last summer
in Eugene, Oregon.

57:34.140 --> 57:37.765
Outside Eugene, Ed.

57:39.765 --> 57:40.765
Yeah?

57:40.974 --> 57:44.724
At night there were lights.
We both saw them.

57:44.807 --> 57:48.807
We never told anyone
outside of our official report,

57:48.932 --> 57:50.849
Our report to the government.

57:52.974 --> 57:54.765
There was a spacecraft.

57:55.807 --> 57:57.932
I saw the creatures.

57:58.015 --> 58:00.974
They led Big Dave onto the craft.

58:01.057 --> 58:04.473
He never told anyone
what they did.

58:04.598 --> 58:06.181
Ann, would you like to...

58:06.306 --> 58:10.848
I cannot repeat it to you,
but this thing goes deep, Ed.

58:10.973 --> 58:13.806
It goes deep
and involves the government.

58:13.848 --> 58:18.055
This was not your wife.
There's a great deal of fear.

58:18.138 --> 58:22.097
You know how certain circles
would-would find it,

58:22.180 --> 58:23.222
The knowledge, a threat.

58:23.305 --> 58:25.722
They-they try to limit it, and...

58:25.805 --> 58:29.722
Ann, would you like to come in,

58:29.805 --> 58:32.513
Sit down?

58:32.638 --> 58:34.596
Maybe have a drink.

58:39.512 --> 58:42.262
Sometimes knowledge
is a curse, Ed.

58:44.137 --> 58:46.846
After this happened,

58:46.971 --> 58:48.304
Things changed.

58:50.804 --> 58:51.929
Big Dave...

58:56.137 --> 58:58.596
He never touched me again.

59:01.512 --> 59:03.096
Tell Doris not to worry.

59:03.179 --> 59:05.804
I know it wasn't her.

59:06.845 --> 59:08.635
Perhaps this will
bring it out

59:08.719 --> 59:10.260
Finally.

59:10.510 --> 59:14.177
Perhaps now
it will all come out.

59:43.759 --> 59:45.259
It stinks.

59:45.551 --> 59:47.176
But it's true.

59:47.301 --> 59:49.634
I don't care it's true, it's not true.
It stinks.

59:49.676 --> 59:52.259
You say he was being blackmailed?
By who? You don't know.

59:52.551 --> 59:54.843
For having an affair.
With who? You don't know.

59:54.968 --> 59:58.551
Did anyone else know about it?
Probably not. You don't know.

59:58.634 --> 01:00:00.717
I knew about it.

01:00:00.800 --> 01:00:02.883
Big Dave told me about it...

01:00:02.967 --> 01:00:05.800
And the spot he was putting himself in
by getting the money.

01:00:05.842 --> 01:00:09.217
Terrific! Your husband backs you up.
That's terrific.

01:00:09.300 --> 01:00:11.092
Come on, you gotta give me
something to work with.

01:00:11.175 --> 01:00:14.049
Freddy Riedenschneider is good,
but he's not a magician.

01:00:14.132 --> 01:00:17.591
He can't just wave his little wand in the air
to make a plausible defense materialize.

01:00:17.674 --> 01:00:20.591
Look at what the other side
is gonna run at us.

01:00:20.674 --> 01:00:23.257
They got the company books
prepared by you,

01:00:23.507 --> 01:00:25.674
Cooked by you.
That's motive.

01:00:25.799 --> 01:00:28.841
They got a murder scene you had access to.
That's opportunity.

01:00:28.966 --> 01:00:31.674
They got that little trimmer thing he was
stabbed in the throat with.

01:00:31.799 --> 01:00:33.924
- A dame's weapon.
- It was Big Dave's.

01:00:34.007 --> 01:00:35.799
Don't interrupt me.
That's means.

01:00:35.841 --> 01:00:38.882
They got a fine, upstanding pillar
of the business community as a victim,

01:00:38.966 --> 01:00:40.591
And then they got you,

01:00:40.674 --> 01:00:43.965
A disgruntled, number-juggling underling,

01:00:44.006 --> 01:00:46.548
Who on the day in question
was drunk as a skunk...

01:00:46.631 --> 01:00:51.547
And whose alibi for the time in question
is being passed out at home, alone.

01:00:51.630 --> 01:00:53.755
I was with her.

01:00:53.880 --> 01:00:55.797
Like I say,

01:00:55.922 --> 01:00:57.505
It stinks.

01:01:05.839 --> 01:01:07.547
I killed him.

01:01:22.046 --> 01:01:25.754
Okay. You killed him.

01:01:27.213 --> 01:01:31.796
Okay, we forget the blackmail thing.
You killed him.

01:01:31.921 --> 01:01:33.171
How come?

01:01:36.504 --> 01:01:39.046
He and Doris, uh,
were having an affair.

01:01:42.879 --> 01:01:44.253
Okay.

01:01:44.503 --> 01:01:46.462
How did you know?

01:01:48.837 --> 01:01:51.044
I just knew.

01:01:51.794 --> 01:01:53.919
A husband knows.

01:01:54.877 --> 01:01:56.794
Will anyone else say they knew?

01:01:56.836 --> 01:01:58.127
And don't say your wife.

01:01:58.169 --> 01:02:00.044
I don't know.

01:02:02.169 --> 01:02:04.461
I don't think so.

01:02:05.836 --> 01:02:07.961
How did you get into the store?

01:02:08.086 --> 01:02:09.836
I took Doris's keys.

01:02:09.961 --> 01:02:14.044
Will anyone say they saw you there,
on your way there, in there, on your way back?

01:02:16.002 --> 01:02:18.086
I don't think so.

01:02:18.211 --> 01:02:21.626
Will anyone corroborate any goddamn part
of your story at all?

01:02:21.710 --> 01:02:25.085
Oh, come on! People,
you can't help each other like that.

01:02:26.585 --> 01:02:28.960
Let's be realistic, now.

01:02:29.043 --> 01:02:33.668
Let's look at our options.
Well, frankly, I don't see any options.

01:02:33.793 --> 01:02:37.750
Look, I cannot present story "A."
I cannot present

01:02:37.834 --> 01:02:40.000
story "B."

01:02:40.125 --> 01:02:43.500
I could plead you for a nutcase,
but you look too composed.

01:02:43.625 --> 01:02:45.625
I could offer a guilty plea,
and in return they don't give you the juice,

01:02:45.750 --> 01:02:47.625
But I don't think you want to spend
the rest of your life in chino.

01:02:47.709 --> 01:02:49.750
I know you didn't hire Freddy Riedenschneider

01:02:49.875 --> 01:02:51.959
To hold your hand at a sentencing hearing.

01:02:52.084 --> 01:02:53.959
You could have gotten
Lloyd Garroway for that.

01:02:54.042 --> 01:02:56.791
No, no, no, no.
We're not giving up yet.

01:02:56.916 --> 01:03:00.041
You hired Freddy Riedenschneider,
It means you're not throwing in the towel.

01:03:00.124 --> 01:03:01.458
I litigate.

01:03:01.583 --> 01:03:03.791
I don't capitulate.

01:03:03.916 --> 01:03:07.249
All right. No options?
We gotta think.

01:03:07.499 --> 01:03:11.791
All right. We go back
to the blackmail thing. Yeah, it titillates.

01:03:11.916 --> 01:03:14.041
It's open-ended,
and it makes him the bad guy.

01:03:14.124 --> 01:03:16.833
You dig around, you never know.
Something unsavory from his past.

01:03:16.958 --> 01:03:20.916
He approaches you to help him with the money,
his past comes back to haunt him. Who's to say?

01:03:20.999 --> 01:03:24.666
Yeah. Yeah. Yeah. Yeah.
Forget the jealous husband thing. That's just silly.

01:03:24.791 --> 01:03:27.081
We're going with the blackmail.
I'll be in touch.

01:03:27.164 --> 01:03:28.831
I'm comin' out!

01:03:37.831 --> 01:03:41.622
Of course there was one person
who could confirm Doris's story,

01:03:41.747 --> 01:03:43.247
Or plenty of it.

01:03:43.497 --> 01:03:46.122
The dry-cleaning pansy.

01:03:46.247 --> 01:03:48.956
But he'd left the hotel,
skipped out on his bill.

01:03:50.497 --> 01:03:53.497
He'd also disappeared
from the residence he gave me,

01:03:53.622 --> 01:03:55.164
Owing two months'rent.

01:03:55.289 --> 01:03:57.706
How could I have been so stupid?

01:03:57.789 --> 01:04:00.455
Handing over $10,000
for a piece of paper.

01:04:02.496 --> 01:04:05.580
And the man gone,
like a ghost.

01:04:05.705 --> 01:04:10.080
Disappeared into thin air
vaporized like the nips at Nagasaki.

01:04:10.163 --> 01:04:11.788
Gone now.

01:04:15.163 --> 01:04:17.705
All gone.

01:04:17.788 --> 01:04:20.912
The money gone,
Big Dave gone,

01:04:20.995 --> 01:04:23.954
Doris going.

01:04:24.037 --> 01:04:26.454
How could I have been so stupid?

01:05:07.827 --> 01:05:11.117
Sooner or later,
everyone needs a haircut.

01:05:13.617 --> 01:05:15.742
We were working for the bank now.

01:05:15.867 --> 01:05:19.659
We kept cutting the hair,
trying to stay afloat,

01:05:19.784 --> 01:05:23.826
Make the payments,
tread the water day by day,

01:05:25.034 --> 01:05:26.784
Day by day.

01:05:30.617 --> 01:05:32.867
Most people think someone's
accused of a crime,

01:05:32.951 --> 01:05:36.117
They haul 'em in and bring 'em to trial,
But it's not like that.

01:05:36.242 --> 01:05:37.866
It's not that fast.

01:05:37.950 --> 01:05:40.950
The wheels of justice turn slow.

01:05:41.075 --> 01:05:43.908
They have the arraignment,
then the indictment,

01:05:43.991 --> 01:05:48.116
And they entertain motions to dismiss
and postpone and change the venue...

01:05:48.200 --> 01:05:50.741
And alter this and that
and the other.

01:05:50.866 --> 01:05:53.700
They impanel a jury,
which bring more motions.

01:05:53.783 --> 01:05:56.700
Then they set a trial date,
and then they change the date.

01:05:56.783 --> 01:05:58.866
And then, often as not,
they'll change it again.

01:05:58.950 --> 01:06:00.700
Not guilty, your honor.

01:06:04.532 --> 01:06:07.115
And through all of it,
we cut the hair.

01:06:13.031 --> 01:06:16.781
Meantime, Freddy Riedenschneider
slept at the Metropole...

01:06:20.489 --> 01:06:22.948
And shoveled it in
at Da Vinci's.

01:06:24.281 --> 01:06:26.781
He'd brought in a private investigator
from Sacramento...

01:06:26.906 --> 01:06:29.781
To nose around
into Big Dave's past.

01:06:48.238 --> 01:06:52.072
I found myself, more and more,
going over to the Abundas's.

01:06:52.155 --> 01:06:55.904
It was a routine we fell into
most every evening.

01:06:55.987 --> 01:06:59.862
I even went when Walter was away
on his research trips.

01:07:02.987 --> 01:07:04.946
He was a genealogist,

01:07:05.071 --> 01:07:08.154
Had traced back his side of the family
seven generations,

01:07:08.279 --> 01:07:10.154
His late wife's eight.

01:07:10.279 --> 01:07:12.612
It seemed like a screwy hobby,

01:07:12.696 --> 01:07:15.195
But then maybe all hobbies are.

01:07:18.611 --> 01:07:22.861
Maybe Walter found something there
in the old county courthouses,

01:07:22.945 --> 01:07:24.986
Hospital file rooms,

01:07:25.111 --> 01:07:27.861
City archives, property rolls,

01:07:27.945 --> 01:07:29.236
Registries.

01:07:30.611 --> 01:07:33.861
Something maybe like what I found
listening to Birdy play.

01:07:34.861 --> 01:07:36.861
Some kind of escape.

01:07:37.695 --> 01:07:39.778
Some kind of peace.

01:08:22.274 --> 01:08:25.774
They got this guy in Germany.

01:08:26.942 --> 01:08:29.608
Fritz something or other.

01:08:30.608 --> 01:08:32.233
Or is it...
Maybe it's Werner.

01:08:32.483 --> 01:08:35.942
Anyway...
He's got this theory.

01:08:37.274 --> 01:08:40.107
You want to test something,
you know, scientifically...

01:08:40.191 --> 01:08:43.232
How the planet
go 'round the sun,

01:08:43.524 --> 01:08:46.066
What sunspots are made of,

01:08:46.191 --> 01:08:48.816
Why the water
comes out of the tap...

01:08:48.941 --> 01:08:52.024
Well, you gotta look at it.

01:08:52.107 --> 01:08:55.689
But sometimes
you look at it...

01:08:55.773 --> 01:08:59.189
Your looking changes it.

01:09:02.023 --> 01:09:05.856
You can't know the reality
of what happened,

01:09:05.939 --> 01:09:07.148
Or what would have happened,

01:09:07.273 --> 01:09:11.106
If you hadn't stuck in
your own goddamn schnozz.

01:09:11.189 --> 01:09:14.481
So there is no
"What happened."

01:09:14.606 --> 01:09:16.231
Looking at something...

01:09:16.523 --> 01:09:18.106
Changes it.

01:09:23.106 --> 01:09:26.022
They call it
the uncertainty principle.

01:09:26.104 --> 01:09:30.729
Sure, it sound screwy,
but even Einstein says
the guy's onto something.

01:09:34.520 --> 01:09:35.938
Science.

01:09:36.979 --> 01:09:38.188
Perception.

01:09:39.229 --> 01:09:40.145
Reality.

01:09:42.854 --> 01:09:43.938
Doubt.

01:09:45.604 --> 01:09:48.813
Reasonable... doubt.

01:09:50.520 --> 01:09:54.063
I'm saying that sometimes
the more you look,

01:09:54.145 --> 01:09:56.229
the less you really know.

01:09:58.020 --> 01:10:01.520
It's a fact, a proved fact.

01:10:01.603 --> 01:10:03.770
In... In a way,

01:10:03.853 --> 01:10:06.228
It's the only fact there is.

01:10:09.520 --> 01:10:13.603
This Heinie even
wrote it out in numbers.

01:10:16.770 --> 01:10:18.687
Burns?

01:10:25.769 --> 01:10:28.644
Subject:
David Allen Brewster,

01:10:28.769 --> 01:10:30.226
Born Brooklyn, 1911.

01:10:30.518 --> 01:10:33.935
Subject educated public schools.
One year case western university.

01:10:34.018 --> 01:10:35.810
Flunks out.

01:10:35.893 --> 01:10:40.060
1931, Retail appliance salesman
in Barnhoff's department store, Cincinnati.

01:10:40.143 --> 01:10:44.060
1933, Meets Ann Nirdlinger.
They marry that year.

01:10:44.143 --> 01:10:46.643
1935, Arrested
on assault complaint.

01:10:46.768 --> 01:10:48.976
Complainant has a broken nose,
couple of broken ribs.

01:10:49.060 --> 01:10:52.851
'36, Another assault beef
at a bar room altercation.

01:10:52.935 --> 01:10:55.601
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
Couple of fistfights, right?
Go to his service record.

01:10:58.268 --> 01:11:00.768
Inducted march 15, 1942.

01:11:00.851 --> 01:11:05.100
Served in a clerical capacity
in the U.S. Naval shipyards at San Diego.

01:11:05.184 --> 01:11:07.642
One fistfight,
broken up by the M.P.S.

01:11:07.767 --> 01:11:11.724
No court-martial.
Honorable discharge, may 8, 1945.

01:11:11.808 --> 01:11:15.933
- Since then, he's been clean.
- Thank you, Barns. Get lost.

01:11:26.183 --> 01:11:27.141
So?

01:11:27.266 --> 01:11:28.516
So?

01:11:30.016 --> 01:11:32.599
This could be your Dolly's
ticket out of the death house.

01:11:32.724 --> 01:11:34.099
So!

01:11:35.682 --> 01:11:36.890
I don't get it.

01:11:36.973 --> 01:11:39.848
Look, chump.

01:11:39.932 --> 01:11:44.432
This is a guy, from what I understand,
told everybody he was a war hero, right?

01:11:44.557 --> 01:11:45.723
Island-hopping,

01:11:45.807 --> 01:11:47.890
Practically liberated,
the pacific all by himself,

01:11:47.973 --> 01:11:50.765
With a knife in one hand,
a gun in the other,

01:11:50.890 --> 01:11:53.640
And 20 yards of jap guts
between his teeth.

01:11:53.723 --> 01:11:56.973
And now it turns out this dope
spent the war sitting on his ass...

01:11:57.057 --> 01:12:00.223
In some boat yard
in San Diego.

01:12:00.473 --> 01:12:02.515
You asked for blackmail.

01:12:02.598 --> 01:12:06.097
Mr. Hail-fellow-well-met,
about to open his own business here,

01:12:06.222 --> 01:12:09.638
Has been lying to everybody in this town
for the last four years,

01:12:09.721 --> 01:12:12.096
Probably including half the people
sitting on that jury.

01:12:12.221 --> 01:12:14.596
Well, it finally caught up with him.

01:12:14.721 --> 01:12:19.221
Somebody knew his dirty little secret,
just like your wife says.

01:12:19.513 --> 01:12:22.763
They called,
they demanded money.

01:12:24.471 --> 01:12:27.763
Did Big Dave say he'd recently
heard from an old friend?

01:12:27.888 --> 01:12:31.805
Did Big Dave mention it was something
about his war service?

01:12:31.930 --> 01:12:35.013
I don't know.
I wasn't there.

01:12:35.096 --> 01:12:38.055
You have to tell us.

01:12:38.138 --> 01:12:41.095
Maybe he specified,
maybe he didn't.

01:12:41.220 --> 01:12:44.220
I'm not putting words
in your mouth, no.

01:12:44.470 --> 01:12:48.929
But the point is that this liar,
this cynical manipulator,

01:12:49.012 --> 01:12:51.929
Turns to you to help him
out of his jam.

01:12:52.054 --> 01:12:53.970
Fat-assed son of a bitch.

01:12:55.719 --> 01:12:59.219
- So who... who actually...
- Who?

01:12:59.511 --> 01:13:01.136
Who?

01:13:01.261 --> 01:13:02.761
I don't know who.

01:13:02.886 --> 01:13:05.969
But the point is that
if Mr. Prosecutor over there...

01:13:06.053 --> 01:13:09.636
Had devoted half the time
he's spent persecuting this woman...

01:13:09.761 --> 01:13:14.052
To even the most cursory investigation
of this schmo's past,

01:13:14.135 --> 01:13:16.052
Then we might know who.

01:13:16.135 --> 01:13:21.010
But we can't know who.
We can't know what really happened.

01:13:21.093 --> 01:13:24.093
Because the more you look,
the less you know.

01:13:26.468 --> 01:13:28.968
But the beauty of it is...

01:13:29.093 --> 01:13:32.135
We don't gotta know.

01:13:32.260 --> 01:13:36.677
We just gotta show that,
god damn it, they don't know.

01:13:36.760 --> 01:13:41.802
Because of Fritz, or Werner,
whatever the hell his name is.

01:13:45.592 --> 01:13:48.466
Freddy Riedenschneider sees daylight.

01:13:48.550 --> 01:13:51.133
We got a real shot at this, folks.
Let's not get cocky.

01:13:51.258 --> 01:13:52.758
Comin' out!

01:14:07.216 --> 01:14:09.050
Big Dave.

01:14:15.091 --> 01:14:17.091
What a dope.

01:14:24.257 --> 01:14:27.174
So maybe Riedenschneider
could fix it for Doris.

01:14:27.257 --> 01:14:29.799
Maybe it would all work out.

01:14:29.882 --> 01:14:31.840
And I thought,

01:14:33.757 --> 01:14:35.549
I hoped,

01:14:35.632 --> 01:14:38.174
That maybe there was a way out
for me as well.

01:14:39.173 --> 01:14:41.923
He was deaf
when he wrote this.

01:14:42.881 --> 01:14:44.089
Who?

01:14:45.673 --> 01:14:46.839
Beethoven.

01:14:48.881 --> 01:14:52.588
He created it, but he never
actually heard it.

01:14:52.713 --> 01:14:55.630
I guess he just heard it all
in his head somehow.

01:15:03.213 --> 01:15:06.713
The girl had talent.
Anyone could see that.

01:15:06.797 --> 01:15:08.797
And she wasn't
some fly-by-nighter.

01:15:08.922 --> 01:15:11.713
She was just a good, clean kid.

01:15:11.797 --> 01:15:16.088
If she was going to have a career,
she'd need a responsible adult...
Looking out for her,

01:15:16.172 --> 01:15:18.713
Some kind of manager.

01:15:20.047 --> 01:15:23.462
She'd have contracts to look at,
be going out on tours,

01:15:23.546 --> 01:15:25.587
Playing on the radio, maybe.

01:15:25.712 --> 01:15:29.754
I could help her sort through all that without
charging her an arm and a leg.

01:15:29.878 --> 01:15:31.836
Just enough to get by.

01:15:36.045 --> 01:15:37.920
Then I could be with her,

01:15:38.045 --> 01:15:40.961
Enough to keep myself
feeling okay.

01:15:42.711 --> 01:15:45.170
Why couldn't that work?

01:15:45.253 --> 01:15:46.795
Why not?

01:15:53.170 --> 01:15:55.544
- Hi, Mr. Crane.
- Hello, Birdy.

01:15:59.044 --> 01:16:00.919
I thought that was real good.

01:16:01.044 --> 01:16:04.502
Yeah, I messed up a little bit
on the, um, on the agitato,

01:16:04.585 --> 01:16:07.919
But if nobody noticed,
then it's okay.

01:16:11.710 --> 01:16:13.877
Oh, this is, um,
a friend of mine.

01:16:14.002 --> 01:16:17.002
Tony, um, Mr. Crane.

01:16:18.627 --> 01:16:20.002
Hello, Tony.

01:16:20.085 --> 01:16:22.043
Hello, sir.

01:16:38.125 --> 01:16:40.083
Congratulations.

01:16:43.167 --> 01:16:45.792
Think I'll be getting home now.

01:16:48.833 --> 01:16:50.750
It was...
nice to meet you, sir.

01:16:50.875 --> 01:16:52.750
You too, Tony.

01:16:56.583 --> 01:16:58.000
Why couldn't it work?

01:16:59.042 --> 01:17:03.124
Anyway, that's what I was thinking in the days
leading up to the trial.

01:17:03.207 --> 01:17:07.082
It seemed like once that was over,
I'd be ready for a new start.

01:17:07.166 --> 01:17:09.499
Freddy Riedenschneider
was busy preparing.

01:17:09.582 --> 01:17:11.832
He was very optimistic.

01:17:11.916 --> 01:17:16.040
And finally it came...
the first day of the trial,

01:17:16.123 --> 01:17:20.123
What Riedenschneider called
'The big show."

01:17:31.706 --> 01:17:35.830
Where's the judge?
How come there's no judge?

01:17:35.914 --> 01:17:37.830
Where's the judge, Ed?

01:17:39.497 --> 01:17:40.455
Riedenschneider.

01:17:40.539 --> 01:17:43.122
How come the judge
doesn't come out?

01:17:43.205 --> 01:17:47.997
The judge comes in last.
He'll come in when Doris gets here.

01:17:48.080 --> 01:17:51.997
So where's Doris?
I thought we started at 10:00.

01:17:52.080 --> 01:17:54.747
Hey, Riedenschneider.
Where's Doris?

01:17:54.872 --> 01:17:56.622
She's late.

01:17:56.705 --> 01:18:00.622
Late?
How can she be late?

01:18:00.747 --> 01:18:03.830
She's in prison, Ed.
None of us are in prison.

01:18:03.914 --> 01:18:07.787
And yet we're not late.
We're on time, Ed.

01:18:07.870 --> 01:18:09.828
How can Doris be late?

01:18:09.912 --> 01:18:12.662
What, they don't have
wake-up calls?

01:18:17.245 --> 01:18:19.453
- All rise.
- No, no.

01:18:20.162 --> 01:18:21.787
Counselors.

01:18:35.787 --> 01:18:37.078
What's going on, Ed?

01:18:37.203 --> 01:18:40.202
I thought there
would be arguments,

01:18:40.452 --> 01:18:42.161
The bailiff and so forth.

01:18:46.994 --> 01:18:49.411
Ed, what is this?

01:18:49.536 --> 01:18:51.661
Is this procedure?

01:19:08.535 --> 01:19:13.534
In the matter of the people v. Doris Crane,

01:19:13.659 --> 01:19:15.909
Case number SR-87249,

01:19:15.992 --> 01:19:17.909
Cause now pending
is hereby dismissed...

01:19:18.034 --> 01:19:20.034
I don't understand it.

01:19:21.742 --> 01:19:25.159
Had a real shot at this.
I could've won this thing.

01:19:25.242 --> 01:19:27.534
Ladies and gentlemen
of the jury,

01:19:27.617 --> 01:19:31.950
Your service is no longer needed...
And you are now discharge.

01:19:33.825 --> 01:19:35.784
She's hanged herself.

01:19:37.909 --> 01:19:42.492
I'd brought her a dress to wear to court,
and she'd used the belt.

01:19:42.575 --> 01:19:45.824
At first I thought she'd figured out somehow
how I fit into it...

01:19:45.908 --> 01:19:49.198
And couldn't stand it,
couldn't stand knowing.

01:19:49.448 --> 01:19:51.782
But that wasn't it, I'd find out later.

01:19:54.698 --> 01:19:58.657
For now, everything
just seemed ruined.

01:20:00.573 --> 01:20:03.073
Freddy Riedenschneider
went back to Sacramento,

01:20:03.157 --> 01:20:06.157
Still shaking his head,
saying it was the biggest disappointment

01:20:06.240 --> 01:20:08.240
Of his professional career.

01:20:08.490 --> 01:20:10.823
Frankie fell to pieces.

01:20:10.907 --> 01:20:13.115
I suspect he was drinking.

01:20:13.240 --> 01:20:16.697
Anyway, he stopped
coming in to work.

01:20:16.822 --> 01:20:21.156
That left me to keep the place going,
or the bank would've taken it.

01:20:23.031 --> 01:20:25.947
I was the principal barber now.

01:20:26.072 --> 01:20:29.156
I hired a new man
for the second chair.

01:20:29.239 --> 01:20:32.739
I'd hired the guy who did the least gabbing
whie he came in for an interview,

01:20:32.864 --> 01:20:36.572
But I guess the new man had only kept quiet
because he was nervous.

01:20:36.697 --> 01:20:39.656
Once he had the job, he talked from the minute
I opened the shop in the morning...

01:20:39.739 --> 01:20:42.488
Until I locked up at night.

01:20:44.738 --> 01:20:47.530
For all I know, he talked to himself
on the way home.

01:20:51.237 --> 01:20:55.195
When I walked home, it seemed like everyone
avoided looking at me,

01:20:55.487 --> 01:20:57.570
As if I'd caught some disease.

01:20:58.654 --> 01:21:02.487
This thing with Doris,
nobody wanted to talk about it.

01:21:04.904 --> 01:21:08.237
It was like I was a ghost
walking down the street.

01:21:10.029 --> 01:21:12.154
And when I got home now,

01:21:15.904 --> 01:21:17.820
The place felt empty.

01:21:25.153 --> 01:21:27.486
I sat in the house,

01:21:30.069 --> 01:21:32.193
But there was nobody there.

01:21:38.735 --> 01:21:40.985
I was a ghost.

01:21:42.068 --> 01:21:44.068
I didn't see anyone.

01:21:44.193 --> 01:21:46.152
No one saw me.

01:21:51.235 --> 01:21:53.485
I was the barber.

01:22:00.901 --> 01:22:04.776
Some bacon and potatoes,
which are supposed to come with it.

01:22:04.901 --> 01:22:08.567
So I pay for it, and I
put the change in my pocket
without really looking...

01:22:08.692 --> 01:22:11.151
'Cause, gosh,
who looks at the change
when you eat there every day?

01:22:11.234 --> 01:22:14.692
Two blocks later I look
at the change she gave me.
Golly, I'm two bits short.

01:22:14.776 --> 01:22:18.484
So I walk back over to Linton's,
find this gal, big argument.

01:22:18.567 --> 01:22:22.151
She doesn't even recall
the transaction.

01:22:22.234 --> 01:22:24.025
Doesn't recall the transaction.
No recollections.

01:22:24.608 --> 01:22:26.774
So I said, "Look, dear.
Go ahead. Look at the menu."

01:22:26.815 --> 01:22:28.940
If you're in before 6:00,
it's the whatchamacallit...

01:22:32.482 --> 01:22:34.440
- The early bird special.
- Yeah, the early riser.

01:22:39.732 --> 01:22:40.857
Crane?

01:22:41.649 --> 01:22:44.065
I'm Crane.

01:22:44.190 --> 01:22:47.065
My name's Diedrickson,
county medical examiner.

01:22:48.607 --> 01:22:49.857
Yeah?

01:22:52.565 --> 01:22:55.440
I just came by
for an informal chat.

01:23:01.481 --> 01:23:03.648
Why don't I
buy you a drink?

01:23:06.898 --> 01:23:08.439
Rye.

01:23:09.606 --> 01:23:11.564
Just coffee.

01:23:11.648 --> 01:23:14.564
You sure you don't want
something stiffer?

01:23:14.648 --> 01:23:16.522
Coffee it is.

01:23:22.147 --> 01:23:26.522
County M.E. Does an autopsy
on anyone who dies in custody.

01:23:27.230 --> 01:23:29.480
I don't know
if you knew that.

01:23:29.563 --> 01:23:30.897
It's routine.

01:23:32.229 --> 01:23:36.687
Doesn't become a matter of public record
unless there's been foul play.

01:23:36.771 --> 01:23:38.687
However,

01:23:38.729 --> 01:23:41.854
I don't think I'm prohibited
from telling you this.

01:23:41.979 --> 01:23:44.979
Of course, I'm not
obliged to either.

01:23:45.062 --> 01:23:47.062
I just don't know.

01:23:48.062 --> 01:23:50.646
But if I were the man,

01:23:50.729 --> 01:23:53.562
I'd want to be told.

01:23:54.729 --> 01:23:56.521
Told what?

01:24:02.812 --> 01:24:05.770
I'm not here to add to your...

01:24:06.478 --> 01:24:07.644
Thanks.

01:24:19.769 --> 01:24:21.769
Your wife was pregnant.

01:24:23.435 --> 01:24:25.185
First trimester.

01:24:29.185 --> 01:24:31.810
There it is.

01:24:32.602 --> 01:24:34.519
I'm sorry.

01:24:36.976 --> 01:24:40.059
Hell, I hope I've done
the right thing.

01:24:44.643 --> 01:24:49.184
My wife and I had not performed
the sex act in many years.

01:25:04.767 --> 01:25:06.017
Well,

01:25:09.516 --> 01:25:12.016
That's really none of my business.

01:25:16.516 --> 01:25:18.016
I'm sorry.

01:25:20.557 --> 01:25:22.182
There it is.

01:25:25.016 --> 01:25:26.849
Good luck, Crane.

01:25:43.890 --> 01:25:47.390
Doris and I had never
really talked much.

01:25:47.515 --> 01:25:50.014
I don't think that's
a bad thing necessarily.

01:25:50.139 --> 01:25:54.514
But it is funny.
Now I wanted to talk.

01:25:54.597 --> 01:25:57.180
Now, with everyone gone,

01:25:57.472 --> 01:26:00.805
I was alone with secrets
I didn't want...

01:26:00.889 --> 01:26:03.847
And no one
to tell 'em to anyway.

01:26:05.055 --> 01:26:08.139
I went to see a woman who was supposed
to have powers in communicating...

01:26:08.222 --> 01:26:11.097
With those who had "Passed across",
as she called it.

01:26:11.222 --> 01:26:13.805
She said that people who had passed across
were picky about

01:26:13.889 --> 01:26:15.679
Who they'd communicate with.

01:26:15.763 --> 01:26:18.554
Not like most people
you run into on this side.

01:26:18.638 --> 01:26:23.179
So you needed a guide,
someone with a gift for talking to souls.

01:26:24.554 --> 01:26:25.888
Give me your hand.

01:26:30.221 --> 01:26:33.679
Well, first she told me that
my wife was in a peachful place,

01:26:33.763 --> 01:26:35.846
That our souls
were still connected,

01:26:35.971 --> 01:26:38.013
That she'd never
stopped loving me...

01:26:38.138 --> 01:26:41.803
Even though she'd done some things
she wasn't proud of.

01:26:43.220 --> 01:26:45.512
Man, she was reading me
like a book.

01:26:47.636 --> 01:26:51.094
She was a phony,
just another gabber.

01:26:51.219 --> 01:26:54.177
I was turning into
Ann Nirdlinger,

01:26:54.427 --> 01:26:56.969
Big Dave's wife

01:26:57.052 --> 01:26:59.886
I had to turn my back
on the old lady,

01:27:00.011 --> 01:27:03.636
On the veils, on the ghosts,

01:27:03.719 --> 01:27:05.677
On the dead,

01:27:05.719 --> 01:27:08.511
Before they all sucked me in.

01:27:20.218 --> 01:27:21.718
Ed?

01:27:21.843 --> 01:27:23.968
How are you holding up?

01:27:24.051 --> 01:27:25.926
Okay, Walter.
Thanks.

01:27:27.885 --> 01:27:29.843
I, uh... I was so damn sorry
to hear about your loss.

01:27:29.968 --> 01:27:32.843
A terrible thing.
It's just damn terrible.

01:27:34.550 --> 01:27:37.092
Uh, Birdy's upstairs.
I'm on long-distance, so...

01:27:37.217 --> 01:27:38.592
Sure, Walter.

01:27:50.175 --> 01:27:52.008
Hello, Birdy.

01:27:52.966 --> 01:27:54.758
Hi, Mr. Crane.

01:27:56.216 --> 01:27:58.591
We haven't seen you since...

01:28:01.174 --> 01:28:03.424
We've certainly missed you.

01:28:06.008 --> 01:28:08.508
Birdy, I've been doing
a lot of thinking.

01:28:11.049 --> 01:28:15.508
There are a lot of things
that haven't worked out for me.

01:28:15.549 --> 01:28:18.674
Life has dealt me some bum cards.

01:28:18.716 --> 01:28:20.674
Or maybe I just haven't played them right.

01:28:20.716 --> 01:28:23.716
Pop doesn't like people
smoking in here.

01:28:29.506 --> 01:28:30.964
I'm sorry.

01:28:31.047 --> 01:28:35.006
Well, sometimes I have a cigarette
when he's away, but never when he's home.

01:28:35.131 --> 01:28:37.672
He can smell it a mile off.

01:28:37.756 --> 01:28:40.589
Well, sure.
It's his house.

01:28:40.714 --> 01:28:43.172
That's what he
keeps telling me.

01:28:44.547 --> 01:28:47.172
Anyway, my point is
you're young,

01:28:47.214 --> 01:28:50.672
A kid, really,
your whole life ahead of you.

01:28:51.922 --> 01:28:56.506
But it's not too soon
to start making opportunities for yourself...

01:28:56.589 --> 01:28:59.505
Before it all washes away.

01:29:01.880 --> 01:29:06.005
Yeah, I guess.
Pop says so too.

01:29:06.088 --> 01:29:08.130
You know, I work
pretty hard at school.

01:29:08.213 --> 01:29:10.755
That's swell.

01:29:10.880 --> 01:29:14.671
However, the music,
if you want to pursue it...

01:29:14.713 --> 01:29:19.670
The lessons from Mrs. Swan,
they'll only take you so far.

01:29:19.712 --> 01:29:22.420
There's this guy
in San Francisco.

01:29:23.212 --> 01:29:25.379
I've made inquiries.

01:29:26.545 --> 01:29:29.669
Everybody says
he's the best.

01:29:29.753 --> 01:29:33.961
Trained people who've gone on to big concert
careers in symphony orchestras, the works.

01:29:34.044 --> 01:29:36.669
His name is Jacques...

01:29:36.711 --> 01:29:38.711
Carcanogues.

01:29:38.753 --> 01:29:41.628
I'm not sure I'm pronouncing it right.
Anyway, he's a frenchman.

01:29:41.711 --> 01:29:44.128
- Oh, boy. A frenchman, huh?
- You've got talent.

01:29:45.544 --> 01:29:48.919
Anybody can see that.
And he's the best.

01:29:49.044 --> 01:29:51.669
If he sees a student
that he thinks has talent,

01:29:51.711 --> 01:29:55.044
He takes them on for next to nothing.
So you're a cinch to be accepted.

01:29:55.086 --> 01:29:58.878
I could cover the costs of the lessons.
Like I said, it's pretty modest.

01:29:59.003 --> 01:30:02.168
- Oh, Jeez, Mr. Crane.
- No, I have to do it.

01:30:02.210 --> 01:30:05.668
I can't stand by and watch
any more things go down the drain.

01:30:05.752 --> 01:30:07.793
You're young.
You don't understand.

01:30:07.877 --> 01:30:12.667
Well, Jeez, Mr. Crane.
I hadn't really thought about a career or stuff.

01:30:14.084 --> 01:30:16.501
Well, I know you haven't.

01:30:17.709 --> 01:30:21.917
Look, just go see him
as a favor to me.

01:30:22.709 --> 01:30:24.042
I talked to this guy.

01:30:24.084 --> 01:30:27.584
He loosened up a little bit
when I told him how talented you were.

01:30:27.709 --> 01:30:29.834
He's agreed to see you
this Saturday.

01:30:31.042 --> 01:30:34.541
He said, uh, maybe you're
a diamond in the rough.

01:30:35.625 --> 01:30:37.041
His words.

01:30:37.125 --> 01:30:39.666
Jeez, I don't know,
Mr. Crane.

01:30:41.958 --> 01:30:44.833
Just go see him
as a favor to me.

01:31:06.874 --> 01:31:08.081
You are the father?

01:31:08.206 --> 01:31:11.539
No, I'm her...
I'm a family friend.

01:31:11.664 --> 01:31:15.664
I am Carcanogues.
You will wait, my dear.

01:31:25.206 --> 01:31:27.039
I speak with you
on the phone, no?

01:31:27.164 --> 01:31:30.789
You have a special interest
in music?

01:31:38.414 --> 01:31:40.705
A music lover,
alors.

01:31:42.205 --> 01:31:44.872
Um, I don't pretend
to be an expert.

01:31:56.787 --> 01:31:58.412
How did she do?

01:31:58.537 --> 01:32:00.746
She seemed like
a very nice girl.

01:32:02.996 --> 01:32:06.662
She play, monsieur,

01:32:06.746 --> 01:32:08.829
Like a very nice girl.

01:32:10.496 --> 01:32:11.621
Stinks.

01:32:11.704 --> 01:32:13.536
Nice girl,

01:32:13.661 --> 01:32:15.620
However, stinks.

01:32:16.703 --> 01:32:18.495
Well, I don't understand.

01:32:18.578 --> 01:32:20.661
Is not so hard to understand.

01:32:20.745 --> 01:32:23.870
Her playing, uh,
very polite.

01:32:23.995 --> 01:32:26.161
Did she make mistakes?

01:32:26.411 --> 01:32:28.828
Mistake? No.

01:32:28.911 --> 01:32:31.495
It say "E-flat,"
she play E-flat.

01:32:31.578 --> 01:32:34.870
Ping, ping. She play
the right note always.

01:32:34.995 --> 01:32:37.453
Well, I don't understand.
No mistakes?

01:32:37.536 --> 01:32:40.995
Look, she's just a kid.
I thought you taught these kids to...

01:32:41.120 --> 01:32:45.034
No, no, no, monsieur.
That is what I cannot teach her, huh?
I cannot teach her to have the soul.

01:32:46.534 --> 01:32:48.201
Hmm, voyez, monsieur.
Look.

01:32:49.659 --> 01:32:53.826
To play the piano
is not about the fingers.

01:32:53.909 --> 01:32:55.909
We make with the fingers.

01:33:01.951 --> 01:33:07.659
But the music, monsieur,
she come from I'interieur, from inside, huh?

01:33:08.743 --> 01:33:10.701
The music,

01:33:10.784 --> 01:33:12.868
She starts here.

01:33:12.993 --> 01:33:15.868
She come out through here.

01:33:15.993 --> 01:33:19.450
Hmm?
Then perhaps,

01:33:19.533 --> 01:33:21.033
Perhaps,

01:33:21.158 --> 01:33:23.825
She can go here.

01:33:28.117 --> 01:33:30.867
Like I said,
I'm not an expert.

01:33:30.992 --> 01:33:34.658
So you can listen to me,
for I am expert.

01:33:37.074 --> 01:33:39.824
Voyez, monsieur.
This girl, nice girl.

01:33:39.907 --> 01:33:43.574
Very clever hands.
Nice girl.

01:33:43.699 --> 01:33:46.824
I think, uh,
perhaps some day...

01:33:47.824 --> 01:33:51.490
She can make
very good typist, huh?

01:33:56.948 --> 01:33:58.281
Voila.

01:34:06.698 --> 01:34:09.156
- I stank, didn't I?
- He didn't say that.

01:34:09.448 --> 01:34:11.823
No, but more or less.

01:34:13.698 --> 01:34:15.031
I'm no expert,

01:34:15.073 --> 01:34:17.990
But there must be a dozen teachers
better than this clown.

01:34:18.073 --> 01:34:19.906
- No, look, really...
- More qualified.

01:34:20.031 --> 01:34:21.906
Goddamn phony.

01:34:22.739 --> 01:34:24.155
Really, it's okay.

01:34:24.405 --> 01:34:28.738
I'm not interested in
playing music professionally.

01:34:28.863 --> 01:34:31.529
You know, I'm not sure
I want a career at all,

01:34:31.654 --> 01:34:34.154
And if I did, I'd probably
be a veterinarian.

01:34:37.904 --> 01:34:39.988
- Veterinarian.
- Yeah.

01:34:41.779 --> 01:34:44.488
But I-I do appreciate
your interest.

01:34:45.446 --> 01:34:46.988
It was nothing.

01:34:47.113 --> 01:34:52.029
I wish I'd played better for you
'cause I know it would've made you real happy.

01:34:55.903 --> 01:34:57.528
You know what you are?

01:34:59.028 --> 01:35:00.528
What?

01:35:00.653 --> 01:35:02.820
You're an enthusiast.

01:35:06.028 --> 01:35:07.653
Yeah, maybe.

01:35:14.612 --> 01:35:18.902
You know, I really do appreciate
the interest you've taken.

01:35:26.527 --> 01:35:28.401
I just wanted to make you happy.

01:35:29.568 --> 01:35:31.651
No, it's really okay.
I wanna do it.

01:35:31.735 --> 01:35:33.110
- Birdy!
- No, it's okay, really.

01:35:33.693 --> 01:35:36.401
Mr. Crane, I wanna do it.
Mr. Crane!

01:35:36.526 --> 01:35:37.985
- Birdy, please don't do that!
- Mr. Crane, please!

01:35:38.068 --> 01:35:40.776
- Heavens to betsy, Birdy!
- Please, Mr. Crane.

01:35:50.860 --> 01:35:54.151
Time slow down
right before in accident,

01:35:54.401 --> 01:35:57.360
And I have time
to think about things.

01:35:59.610 --> 01:36:03.150
I thought about what an undertaker
had told me once.

01:36:03.442 --> 01:36:07.150
That your hair keeps growing
for a while, anyway,

01:36:07.400 --> 01:36:09.484
After you die.

01:36:11.649 --> 01:36:13.733
And then it stops.

01:36:18.024 --> 01:36:21.649
I thought,
"What keeps it growing?"

01:36:23.191 --> 01:36:25.858
Is it like a plant in soil?

01:36:27.108 --> 01:36:29.524
What goes out of the soil?

01:36:29.608 --> 01:36:31.149
The soul?

01:36:33.148 --> 01:36:36.148
And when does the hair
realize that it's gone?

01:37:26.688 --> 01:37:27.855
Hello!

01:37:28.855 --> 01:37:31.730
I noticed you still have
pea stone in your driveway.

01:37:32.896 --> 01:37:37.687
Of course you have to rejuvenate
that every couple of years, don't you?
When the pea stone thins out?

01:37:37.812 --> 01:37:40.812
Ha.
Where does it go, huh?

01:37:40.937 --> 01:37:42.770
Like the odd sock.

01:37:42.854 --> 01:37:48.187
'Course, you know where it goes.
You probably pick pieces of it
off your lawn all the time,

01:37:48.395 --> 01:37:51.854
Churn it up with your lawn mover,
sweep it off your porch there.

01:37:51.937 --> 01:37:55.603
- Pain in the neck.
- Never bothered me.

01:37:55.686 --> 01:37:57.853
Well, have you ever
considered tar macadam?

01:37:57.936 --> 01:38:00.728
People think it's just for public works
or commercial purposes,

01:38:00.853 --> 01:38:04.019
But we have the technology now
to bring it to the homeowner,

01:38:04.144 --> 01:38:06.811
Individual consumer,
at very competitive prices.

01:38:06.894 --> 01:38:11.102
Mind if I show you the specifications?
Afternoon, Ma'am.

01:38:11.185 --> 01:38:13.185
What are you selling?

01:38:15.852 --> 01:38:18.768
Ma'am, I was just telling your husband here
about tar macadam.

01:38:18.852 --> 01:38:20.810
For your home driveway here.

01:38:20.893 --> 01:38:24.685
Here's the brochure.
It's the modern way to...

01:38:24.768 --> 01:38:25.810
Get lost.

01:38:41.852 --> 01:38:43.184
Jesus.

01:39:37.431 --> 01:39:39.014
Doris.

01:39:40.639 --> 01:39:43.806
Don't say anything.
I'm fine.

01:40:04.555 --> 01:40:06.013
Crane.

01:40:06.763 --> 01:40:08.180
Mr. Crane?

01:40:10.805 --> 01:40:12.930
Are you there?

01:40:13.013 --> 01:40:14.805
Are you awake?

01:40:16.888 --> 01:40:18.805
He's comin' around.

01:40:20.013 --> 01:40:22.846
Can you talk, sir?
These men have to talk to you.

01:40:22.929 --> 01:40:25.679
Are you awake? Sir?

01:40:25.762 --> 01:40:27.971
He's... he's awake.
Go ahead.

01:40:28.096 --> 01:40:29.803
Are you awake?

01:40:29.886 --> 01:40:31.386
Is he awake?

01:40:31.511 --> 01:40:34.803
Crane, as soon as you're conscious,
we have to tell you that...

01:40:34.886 --> 01:40:37.845
- Uh, is he conscious?
- His eyes are open.

01:40:38.678 --> 01:40:40.053
Uh, you're under arrest.

01:40:40.136 --> 01:40:42.511
Soon as the doctor lets us,
we gotta move you.

01:40:42.595 --> 01:40:45.720
Does he understand that?
We're supposed to tell him.
Are you conscious?

01:40:45.845 --> 01:40:49.470
- They'll take you to the prison hospital.
- Under arrest for murder.

01:40:53.969 --> 01:40:56.844
What?
What'd he say?

01:40:56.927 --> 01:41:00.094
Birdy. Uh, the girl.
No, the girl's okay.

01:41:00.177 --> 01:41:01.802
Broken clavicle.

01:41:01.885 --> 01:41:04.135
That's a collarbone, Crane.
It's broken.

01:41:04.385 --> 01:41:05.510
She's okay, though.

01:41:05.635 --> 01:41:09.427
So he understands, then,
he's under arrest for murder?

01:41:09.510 --> 01:41:10.885
- Big Dave.
- Huh?

01:41:12.677 --> 01:41:14.344
What?
What'd he say?

01:41:14.427 --> 01:41:16.135
He said okay.

01:41:16.385 --> 01:41:17.844
Is that what he said?

01:41:19.969 --> 01:41:23.593
You're under arrest for the murder
of Creighton Tolliver.

01:41:23.676 --> 01:41:25.633
You understad that?

01:41:25.717 --> 01:41:27.592
Does he understand?

01:41:29.550 --> 01:41:30.883
The pansy.

01:41:33.425 --> 01:41:37.467
A kid diving in a water holeoutside of town
had found his car.

01:41:37.550 --> 01:41:39.633
They winched it out...

01:41:39.758 --> 01:41:43.383
And found he'd been beaten,
just like Big Dave said.

01:41:44.842 --> 01:41:46.717
Beaten to death.

01:41:48.967 --> 01:41:53.633
Inside his briefcase
were the partnership papers I'd signed,

01:41:53.717 --> 01:41:56.467
Showing that I'd
given him ten grand.

01:41:57.633 --> 01:42:01.382
For the district attorney,
that made it fall into place.

01:42:01.507 --> 01:42:03.924
I'd gotten Doris
to steal the money.

01:42:04.007 --> 01:42:08.007
The pansy had gotten wise somehow,
so I had to kill him to cover my tracks.

01:42:08.132 --> 01:42:10.632
On the arraignment calendar,

01:42:10.757 --> 01:42:12.548
People v. Edward Crane.

01:42:12.673 --> 01:42:13.798
I was in a spot.

01:42:13.881 --> 01:42:16.631
You are charged
in a one-count complaint...

01:42:16.756 --> 01:42:21.465
I called in Freddy Riedenschneider
and signed the house over to him.

01:42:21.548 --> 01:42:23.923
He said he didn't ordinarily
work that cheap,

01:42:24.006 --> 01:42:27.506
But he figured he owed me something
since the last one hadn't played out.

01:42:27.631 --> 01:42:30.131
- How do you now plead?
- We plead not guilty, your honor.

01:42:30.423 --> 01:42:33.630
I tried to tell him the whole story,
but Riedenschneider stopped me.

01:42:33.714 --> 01:42:35.672
He said the story
made his head hurt.

01:42:35.755 --> 01:42:39.089
He didn't see any way of using it
without putting me on the hot seat...

01:42:39.172 --> 01:42:42.505
- For the murder of Big Dave.
- Trial date is set for Monday a week.

01:42:44.672 --> 01:42:47.880
He told me not to worry, though.
Said he'd think of something.

01:42:50.089 --> 01:42:53.005
They put me
on 24-hour death watch,

01:42:53.089 --> 01:42:57.964
So that I couldn't cheat justice
like they said my wife had done.

01:42:58.047 --> 01:43:01.005
But in front of the jury,
they had it that Doris was a saint.

01:43:01.130 --> 01:43:04.462
The whole plan had been mine.

01:43:04.545 --> 01:43:07.753
I was a svengali
who had forced Doris to join

01:43:07.837 --> 01:43:10.128
My criminal enterprise.

01:43:10.378 --> 01:43:11.920
On and on it went,

01:43:12.003 --> 01:43:16.462
How I'd used Doris,
then let her take the fall.

01:43:16.545 --> 01:43:20.462
That stuff smarted because some of it
was close to being true.

01:43:22.920 --> 01:43:25.587
And then it was
Riedenschneider's turn.

01:43:33.670 --> 01:43:37.711
Ladies and gentlemen, members of the jury,
citizens of Santa Rosa,

01:43:37.836 --> 01:43:41.169
We've just heard from the district attorney
a rather lurid description...

01:43:41.419 --> 01:43:43.086
Of a truly despicable man.

01:43:43.169 --> 01:43:47.377
I gotta hand it to him.
He tossed a lot of sand in their eyes,

01:43:47.502 --> 01:43:50.586
He talked about how
I'd lost my place in the universe,

01:43:50.669 --> 01:43:54.794
How I was too ordinary to be
the criminal mastermind...

01:43:54.919 --> 01:43:56.793
The D.A. Made me out to be,

01:43:56.876 --> 01:44:01.793
How there was some greater scheme at work
that the state had yet to unravel.

01:44:01.876 --> 01:44:06.960
And he threw in some of the old truth stuff
he hadn't had the chance to trot out for Doris.

01:44:07.043 --> 01:44:10.500
May at first look at these lines
and see only the chaos
of a work of modern art.

01:44:10.584 --> 01:44:14.667
He told them to look at me,
look at me close.

01:44:14.792 --> 01:44:18.042
That the closer they looked,
the less sense it would all make.

01:44:18.167 --> 01:44:21.667
This human, this barber.

01:44:21.792 --> 01:44:24.959
That I wasn't the kind of guy
to kill a guy,

01:44:25.042 --> 01:44:28.000
That I was the barber,
for Christ's sake.

01:44:28.125 --> 01:44:31.584
I was just like them,
an ordinary man.

01:44:31.667 --> 01:44:35.000
Guilty of living in a world
that had no place for me, yeah.

01:44:35.084 --> 01:44:37.625
Guilty of wanting to be
a dry cleaner, sure.

01:44:37.709 --> 01:44:38.959
But not of murder.

01:44:39.042 --> 01:44:43.124
But most specifically,
this is a barber's dilemma.

01:44:43.416 --> 01:44:45.624
For he is modern man.

01:44:45.708 --> 01:44:47.790
He said I was modern man.

01:44:47.873 --> 01:44:49.707
He is your reflection.

01:44:49.790 --> 01:44:51.332
And if they voted to convict me,

01:44:51.457 --> 01:44:55.332
They'd be practically cinching the noose
around their own necks.

01:44:55.457 --> 01:44:58.790
He told them to look not at the facts,
but at the meaning of the facts.

01:44:58.873 --> 01:45:02.040
And then he said
the facts had no meaning.

01:45:02.165 --> 01:45:05.582
It was a pretty good speech
and even had me going,

01:45:05.665 --> 01:45:07.082
Until Frankie interrupted it.

01:45:10.415 --> 01:45:12.332
What kind of man are you?

01:45:12.457 --> 01:45:15.039
What kind of man are you?

01:45:15.164 --> 01:45:16.872
Move for a mistrial!
Your honor!

01:45:16.956 --> 01:45:18.872
What kind of man are you?

01:45:18.997 --> 01:45:20.456
Move for a mistrial.

01:45:20.581 --> 01:45:23.831
Well, he got his mistrial,
but the well had run dry.

01:45:23.956 --> 01:45:25.872
There was nothing left to mortgage.

01:45:25.997 --> 01:45:30.456
Riedenschneider went home,
and the court appointed Lloyd Garroway,

01:45:30.539 --> 01:45:32.664
Who threw me
on the mercy of the court.

01:45:32.789 --> 01:45:35.539
Your honor,
we plead guilty...

01:45:35.664 --> 01:45:38.830
With extenuating circumstances.

01:45:38.955 --> 01:45:41.496
It was my only chance,
he said.

01:45:41.621 --> 01:45:45.038
I guess that meant
I never had a chance.

01:45:47.495 --> 01:45:52.662
He wasn't buying any of that
modern man stuff, or the uncertainty stuff,

01:45:52.787 --> 01:45:54.495
Or any of the mercy stuff either.

01:45:54.620 --> 01:45:56.870
This man is a menace
to society.

01:45:56.954 --> 01:46:00.454
Nope, he was going
by the book,

01:46:00.579 --> 01:46:03.120
And the book said
I got the chair.

01:46:03.412 --> 01:46:05.870
He has forfeited the right
to his own life.

01:46:05.995 --> 01:46:08.329
So here I am,

01:46:08.454 --> 01:46:10.954
At first I didn't know
how I got here.

01:46:11.037 --> 01:46:13.037
I knew step by step,
of course,

01:46:13.162 --> 01:46:16.745
Which is what I've told you,
step by step.

01:46:16.829 --> 01:46:20.744
But I couldn't see any pattern.

01:46:20.828 --> 01:46:22.453
Now that I'm near the end,

01:46:22.494 --> 01:46:25.536
I'm glad that this men's magazine
paid me to tell my story.

01:46:25.703 --> 01:46:29.161
Writing it has helped me
sort it all out.

01:46:29.411 --> 01:46:31.118
They're paying me
flve cents a word,

01:46:31.368 --> 01:46:33.785
So you'll pardon me if sometimes I've told you
more than you wanted to know.

01:46:35.618 --> 01:46:39.077
But now all the disconnected
things seem to hook up.

01:46:40.118 --> 01:46:42.827
That's the funny thing
about going away,

01:46:42.952 --> 01:46:45.327
Knowing the date
you're going to die.

01:46:46.535 --> 01:46:50.452
And the men's magazine
wanted me to tell how that felt.

01:47:15.826 --> 01:47:19.826
Well, it's like pulling away
from the maze.

01:47:21.492 --> 01:47:24.115
While you're in the maze,
you go throught willy-nilly,

01:47:24.407 --> 01:47:26.865
Turning where you think
you have to turn,

01:47:26.990 --> 01:47:29.032
Banging into the dead ends,

01:47:29.115 --> 01:47:30.990
One thing after another.

01:47:36.615 --> 01:47:38.490
But you get
some distance on it,

01:47:38.615 --> 01:47:40.532
And all those twists
and turns...

01:47:40.657 --> 01:47:44.990
Why, they're the shape
of your life.

01:47:46.907 --> 01:47:48.990
It's hard to explain.

01:47:51.699 --> 01:47:55.074
But seeing it whole
gives you some peace.

01:48:29.029 --> 01:48:32.029
The men's magazine
also asked about remorse.

01:48:32.154 --> 01:48:36.987
Yeah, I guess I'm sorry
about the pain I caused other people.

01:48:38.154 --> 01:48:40.862
But I don't regret anything.

01:48:40.946 --> 01:48:42.862
Not a thing.

01:48:42.946 --> 01:48:44.612
I used to.

01:48:44.696 --> 01:48:47.571
I used to regret
being the barber.

01:49:52.151 --> 01:49:54.984
I don't know
where I'm being taken.

01:49:56.692 --> 01:49:59.567
I don't know what I'll find
beyond the earth and sky,

01:50:00.775 --> 01:50:02.608
But I'm not afraid to go.

01:50:04.108 --> 01:50:07.524
Maybe the things I don't understand
will be clearer there,

01:50:07.607 --> 01:50:09.899
Like when a fog blows away.

01:50:12.649 --> 01:50:14.732
Maybe Doris will be there.

01:50:15.691 --> 01:50:19.357
And maybe there
I can tell her...

01:50:19.482 --> 01:50:21.482
All those things...

01:50:22.524 --> 01:50:25.441
They don't have words for here.

